    <body>
        <div xml:id="AN9-kilavi"></div>
        <div xml:id="AN9">
            <lg type="edition"><l>kolviṉaip polinta kūrṅkuṟum <choice><seg>peḵkiṉ</seg><seg>puḻukiṉ</seg></choice></l>
<l>villōr tūṇi vīṅkap peyta</l>
<l>vappunuṉai <choice><seg>yēyppala</seg><seg>yēyppa</seg></choice> varumpiya viruppaic</l>
<l>ceppaṭa raṉṉa ceṅkuḻai yakantō</l>
<l>ṟiḻuti ṉaṉṉa tīmpuḻaṟ ṟuyvā</l>
<l>yuḻutukāṇ ṭuḷaiya vāki yārkaḻal</l>
<l>pāli vāṉiṟ kāloṭu <choice><seg>pāṟit</seg><seg>māṟit</seg></choice></l>
<l>tuppi ṉaṉṉa ceṅkōṭ ṭiyavi</l>
<l>ṉeyttōr mīmicai niṇattiṟ parikku</l>
<l>matta naṇṇiya vaṅkuṭic cīṟūrk</l>
<l>koṭunuṇ ṇōti makaḷi rōcciya</l>
<l>toṭimā <choice><seg>ṇulakkai</seg><seg>ṇulakkait</seg></choice> tūṇṭuraṟ pāṇi</l>
<l>neṭumāl varaiya kuṭiñaiyō ṭiraṭṭuṅ</l>
<l>kuṉṟupiṉ ṉoḻiyap pōki <choice><seg>yuranturantu</seg><seg>yurantantu</seg></choice></l>
<l>ñāyiṟup paṭiṉu mūrcēyt <choice><seg>teṉṉātu</seg><seg>teṉātu</seg></choice></l>
<l>tuṉaipari turakkun tuñcāc celavi</l>
<l>ṉemmiṉum viraintuval leytip paṉmā</l>
<l>ṇōṅkuyar nalli loruciṟai <choice><seg>nilaiiyap</seg><seg>nilaiip</seg></choice></l>
<l>pāṅkarp palli paṭutoṟum paravik</l>
<l>kaṉṟupuku mālai niṉṟō ḷeytik</l>
<l>kaikaviyāc ceṉṟu kaṇputaiyāk <choice><seg>kuṟukip</seg><seg>kuṟuki</seg></choice></l>
<l>piṭikkai yaṉṉa piṉṉakan tīṇṭit</l>
<l>toṭikkai taivarat <choice><seg>tōyntaṉṟu kollō</seg><seg>tōyntaṉṟu kollē</seg></choice></l>
<l>nāṇoṭu miṭainta kaṟpiṉ vāṇuta</l>
<l>lantīṅ kiḷavik kuṟumakaṇ</l>
<l><choice><seg>meṉṟō</seg><seg>meṉṟōḷ</seg></choice> <choice><seg>ṇacaiic</seg><seg>peṟanacaiic</seg></choice> <choice><seg>ceṉṟaveṉ</seg><seg>ceṉṟave</seg></choice> ṉeñcē.</l></lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Past little villages with pretty homes that lie by the road,</l>
<l rend="indent">	where in every place the sprouts, red as copper plates,</l>
<l><choice><seg>	of the </seg><seg>	of the budding </seg></choice> Mahua <choice><seg>trees that have grown many buds </seg><seg>trees, so as to </seg></choice> <choice><seg>resembling </seg><seg>resemble </seg></choice> the arrow tips</l>
<l rend="indent">	put, for the quiver to swell, by the bowmen</l>
<l rend="indent">	with <choice><seg>sharp, wicked blades </seg><seg>sharp short arrow-heads </seg></choice> that flourish in murderous work,</l>
<l rend="indent">	are <choice><seg>scattered </seg><seg>changed </seg></choice> by the wind like hail from the sky,</l>
<l rend="indent">	[their] stems having become loose as they are visibly holed</l>
<l rend="indent">	after the soft fibre had been ploughed for the tubes sweet as ghee,</l>
<l rend="indent">	[and] spread, like fat on top of blood,</l>
<l rend="indent">	on the ways with peaks red as coral,</l>
<l><choice><seg>driving mightily, </seg><seg>applying strength, </seg></choice> going, for the hills to stay behind,</l>
<l rend="indent">	where the beat of the mortars pounded by pestles glorious for [their] rings</l>
<l rend="indent">	raised by women with curly fine hair</l>
<l rend="indent">	sound along with the rock owl from the long dark mountain,</l>
<l>without saying, although the sun has set, “the village is far”,</l>
<l>faster than us</l>
<l>in going without sleeping that drives the rushing horses</l>
<l rend="indent">	reaching quickly, many times,</l>
<l>reaching her who, in the evening when the calves enter, stands</l>
<l rend="indent">	in prayer each time when nearby the gecko calls,</l>
<l><choice><seg>	which had settled </seg><seg>	settling </seg></choice> in one wing of the lofty high good house,</l>
<l>going, enfolding [her] hand, nearing, covering [her] eyes,</l>
<l><choice><seg>seizing </seg><seg>gripping </seg></choice> [her] <choice><seg>braids, </seg><seg>braid, </seg></choice> [long] like the trunk of an elephant cow,</l>
<l>did it touch, caressingly, [her] bangled <choice><seg>hand,</seg><seg>hand?,</seg></choice> </l>
<l><choice><seg>– my heart that went in </seg><seg>– my heart that went </seg></choice> longing <choice><seg>for </seg><seg>to obtain </seg></choice> the soft shoulders</l>
<l>of the little woman with pretty sweet speech,</l>
<l>a bright forehead [and] a fidelity mingled with <choice><seg>modesty<note place="foot">The connotation of nāṇ in connection with kaṟpu is not captured very well by “shame”; it expresses the idea that SHE is faithfully waiting for her man, controlling her feelings and not making an outward display of her emotions as she would not be able to help doing in times of kaḷavu.</note>?</seg><seg>modesty.</seg></choice> </l></lg>
        </div>
    </body>
